[Comment "short-and-sweet-the-sicilian-dragon/course/31190, variation/5712279"]

1. e4 {Hello and welcome to this course on The Sicilian Dragon, one of the most 
popular variations of the Sicilian defense. An interesting and sharp defense. At 
some point, every Sicilian player tries their hand at playing the Dragon. Why is 
the Dragon Sicilian so popular? Besides being a very aggressive opening with 
lots of opportunity for sharp tactics, it is a relatively easy to play system 
with clear attacking plans and ideas for the Black Player. The modern form of 
the Dragon was originated by German master Louis Paulsen around 1880. It was 
played frequently by Henry Bird that decade and was eventually recognized around 
1900 when it started being employed by Harry Nelson Pillsbury and other masters. 
So, why is it called The Dragon and who thought of the name? The earliest known 
printed reference, found by chess historian Edward Winter, is in the Jan-Feb 
1914 issue of Wiener Schachzeitung. Russian chess master Fyodor Dus-Chotimirsky 
claims in his 1953 autobiography that he coined the term 'Dragon Variation' in 
1901. He thought Black's pawn structure resembled the star constellation Draco. 
Pretty cool huh?} c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and 
is also the most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for 
White's pieces faster. An open game is upcoming.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking 
the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 $5 {And here we have our lovely system: The Dragon! It 
is one of the most played defences against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player 
began their Sicilian career playing the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's 
piece development and the clear plans available to him!} 6. Be3 {[%cal 
Bf2f3,Bg2g4,Bh2h4,Bd1d2,Be1c1] At this point White has a lot of other options, 
which are extensively looked at in the main course. In particular:} ({• the 
Classical} 6. Be2 {;}) ({•} 6. Bc4 {;}) ({• the fianchetto} 6. g3 {;}) 
({•} 6. f4 {;}) ({•} 6. Bb5+ {;}) ({•} 6. h3 {followed by an early g4;}) 
({•} 6. Bd3 {;}) ({• and} 6. Bg5 {.}) {However, 6. Be3 is the most popular 
and most dangerous attempt by White, who is preparing a set-up that involves 
Qd2, f3, Queenside castling and a quick pawn storm against Black's Kingside.} 
Bg7 7. f3 a6 $1 {[%cal Ga6b5,Bb7b5][%csl Gb5]} ({The main lines continue with} 
7... O-O 8. Qd2 Nc6) {or} (7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O {. Instead my suggestion is to 
play the sideline 7... a6, delaying castling and the development of our Knight 
to c6, instead starting immediate counterplay on the Queenside.}) {Why does 7 
... a6 deserve an exclamation mark? • 1. It begins counterplay on the 
Queenside as quickly as possible. • 2. It delays castling Kingside, which 
means the attack on the Black King is going to be postponed, and then castling 
Queenside is an option for Black as well. • 3. It controls the square on b5, 
which is an important square that is attacked no less than three times by White. 
• 4. It depends on ideas rather than memorization. *Please note:* It is 
impossible to provide an answer to all the critical tries against the Sicilian 
Dragon, of which there are many, in a short and sweet course. Instead I have 
selected 20 lines from my larger repertoire course that will give you a good 
sense of the typical ideas for Black in this dynamic opening!} *

