[Comment "short-and-sweet-the-sicilian-dragon/course/31190, variation/5712278"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 Nc6 (7... 
a6 $5 {Will be recommended in the course.}) 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bc4 Bd7 {[%cal 
Ba8c8,Gc8c2] Making space for the Rook to go to c8.} 10. Bb3 Rc8 {This Rook is 
on the c-file, glaring down at White's King after he castles Queenside.} 11. h4 
{[%cal Bh4h5] This is played with the intention of later opening the h-file.} h5 
{[%cal Gh5g4][%csl Gg4] Stopping h5.} 12. O-O-O Ne5 {[%cal Be5c4][%csl Gc4] 
Heading for the useful c4-square.} 13. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5e7]} Rc5 {Black wants to 
eventually double Rooks on the c-file.} 14. Kb1 Re8 {[%cal Ge8e7] Overprotecting 
the p-e7.} 15. g4 hxg4 16. h5 {Opening the h-file.} Nxh5 17. Rxh5 gxh5 18. Qh2 
{Threatening Qxh5, followed by Rh1.} Ng6 19. Qxh5 Qa5 {[%cal Gc5g5,Ga5g5][%csl 
Rg5] Attacking the Bishop on g5.} 20. f4 {[%cal Bf4f5]} Rxg5 {In order to stop 
the f5-push.} 21. fxg5 e6 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge6f5][%csl Gf5,Gd5] Crucially supporting 
the (f5 & d5) squares.} 22. Nf5 $5 exf5 23. Qxg6 {[%cal Gb3g8] Making use of the 
f7-pin!} Be6 {[%csl Rg6] Now the Queen is attacked.} 24. Qh5 fxe4 {[%cal 
Ga5e5,Ge5g5] Opening the fifth rank for the Queen.} 25. Rf1 Qe5 {Bringing the 
Queen to the defence.} 26. Rxf7 {[%cal Gb3f7,Gh5f7] Making use of the Bishop on 
b3!} Bxb3 $5 {This Bishop is dangerous, so Black needs to exchange it off.} 27. 
axb3 {And now White needs to follow up.} g3 28. Ka2 Rf8 {[%cal Bf8f7] Getting 
rid of the annoying Rook.} 29. Rxf8+ Kxf8 {[%cal Bg3g1] Threatening g2 - g1.} 
30. Qg4 e3 31. g6 e2 32. Qf3+ (32. Nxe2 $4 Qxb2#) Ke8 33. Qf7+ {Looking for 
counter-play.} Kd8 34. Qg8+ Kd7 35. Qf7+ Qe7 36. Qf5+ Kd8 37. Qa5+ b6 {[%cal 
Be2e1] White has no more checks.} 38. Qd5 {Looking for some more checks.} e1=Q 
39. Qa8+ Kd7 40. Qb7+ Ke8 {[%cal Be7d8,Be7d7] And White resigned, because the 
Queen on e7 covers any more checks.} 0-1

