1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. Be2 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Qd2 
O-O 9. O-O-O Bd7 10. h4 h5 11. f3 Rc8 {We have reached a kind of Yugoslav 
attack, where White developed his light-squared Bishop to e2 rather than the 
very active diagonal on c4!} 12. g4 {Provoking ... hxg4, which would then be met 
by h5, and White would open the h-file.} hxg4 13. h5 Nxh5 14. fxg4 Ng3 
{Attacking both the Rook on h1 and the Bishop on f1.} 15. Rh3 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 e5 
17. Be3 Nxe2+ 18. Qxe2 {White needs to take back with the Queen, in order to 
keep the pawn on g4 protected!} Rxc3 $1 {The typical sac, played with the idea 
of destroying the Queenside pawn structure.} 19. bxc3 Qc8 $1 {Forking both the 
pawn on c3 and the pawn on g4.} 20. Rh4 Qxc3 21. Bh6 Bxg4 $1 22. Rxg4 (22. Qxg4 
$2 Bxh6+ 23. Rxh6 Qe3+ $19 {And the Rook on h6 will be taken.}) Bxh6+ 23. Kb1 
Qb4+ 24. Ka1 Rc8 {Bringing the Rook into the game.} 25. Qd3 Rc4 26. Rb1 (26. 
Qxd6 $2 Qc3+ 27. Kb1 Rb4+ $19 {When White needs to give up his Queen.}) Qc5 
{Attacking the pawn on c2.} 27. Rg2 Be3 {Heading for the d4-square.} 28. Rb3 
Bd4+ 29. Kb1 a5 {Improving the Queenside pawns.} 30. a3 b5 31. c3 a4 32. cxd4 
Rxd4 $19 {[%cal Ga4b3,Gd4d3][%csl Rb3,Rd3] Attacking both the Rook on b3 and the 
Queen on d3.} 1/2-1/2

