1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and is also the 
most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for White's 
pieces faster.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 {And here we 
have our lovely system: The Dragon! It is one of the most played defences 
against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player began their Sicilian career playing 
the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's piece development and the clear plans 
available to him!} 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 ({The main lines continue with} 7... O-O 
8. Qd2 Nc6) {or} (7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O {. Instead my suggestion is to play the 
sideline 7... a6, delaying castling and the development of our Knight to c6, 
instead starting immediate counterplay on the Queenside.}) {Why does 7 ... a6 
deserve an exclamation mark? • 1. It begins counterplay on the Queenside as 
quickly as possible. • 2. It delays castling Kingside, which means the attack 
on the Black King is going to be postponed, and then castling Queenside is an 
option for Black as well. • 3. It controls the square on b5, which is an 
important square that is attacked no less than three times by White. • 4. It 
depends on ideas rather than memorization. *Please note:* It is impossible to 
provide an answer to all the critical tries against the Sicilian Dragon, of 
which there are many, in a short and sweet course. Instead I have selected 20 
lines from my larger repertoire course that will give you a good sense of the 
typical ideas for Black in this dynamic opening!} 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. O-O-O b5 
{Beginning counterplay.} 10. Nc6 {[%csl Rd8] Threatening the Queen. White is 
trying to make use of the weakened c6-square, which was created by ... b5.} Qc7 
11. Nb4 {[%cal Bb4d5][%csl Gd5] And this is the point of White's idea; he gains 
even greater control over the d5-square.} Bb7 {[%cal Gb7d5] In order to fight 
for control of the d5-square.} 12. Nbd5 {Going directly to d5, will only help 
Black.} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 14. exd5 Nb6 $15 {[%cal 
Gb6d5,Gb6c4,Gb6a4,Ba8c8,Be8g8][%csl Rd5] The d5-pawn is weak because White 
cannot use the c-pawn to support it. The d5-pawn also restricts the movement of 
the Bishop on f1. The c-file is a good resource for Black to use, in an attack 
on the White King. ...Na4 is a good idea to keep in mind as well!} *

