typical ideas for Black in this dynamic opening!} 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. g4 b5 10. Nc6 
{[%csl Rd8]} Qc7 11. Nxe7 {[%cal Bg4g5,Bc3d5,Gg5f6,Gd5c7,Gd5e7] The sharpest 
line! This is one of those lines where you really need to know what to do.} Bb7 
{[%cal Gb7d5][%csl Gd5] Adding another piece to fight for control of the 
d5-square.} 12. Ned5 Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Bxd5 {Getting rid of that annoying Knight!} 
14. Qxd5 {The a8-Rook is threatened.} O-O {[%cal Gf8a8,Gg7b2][%csl Rb2] To 
protect the Rook.} (15... Rc8 $5 {is also playable.}) 15. O-O-O Rfc8 {[%cal 
Gc8c2][%csl Rc2] Threatening a mate in one. Black is a pawn down but has a much 
more active position!} 16. Rd2 $2 Bxb2+ $1 {Making use of the unprotected Bishop 
on e3. The golden rule: 'Always try to avoid having unprotected pieces'.} 17. 
Kxb2 Qc3+ $17 {[%cal Bc3e3][%csl Rb2,Re3] Forking both the King and the Bishop, 
after which Black is much better because White's King is very weak.} *

