deserve an exclamation mark? • 1. It begins counterplay on the Queenside as 
quickly as possible. • 2. It delays castling Kingside, which means the attack 
on the Black King is going to be postponed, and then castling Queenside is an 
option for Black as well. • 3. It controls the square on b5, which is an 
important square that is attacked no less than three times by White. • 4. It 
depends on ideas rather than memorization. *Please note:* It is impossible to 
provide an answer to all the critical tries against the Sicilian Dragon, of 
which there are many, in a short and sweet course. Instead I have selected 20 
lines from my larger repertoire course that will give you a good sense of the 
typical ideas for Black in this dynamic opening!} 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. g4 b5 10. Nc6 
Qc7 11. Nxe7 {The sharpest line! This is one of those lines where you really 
need to know what to do.} Bb7 {Adding another piece to fight for control of the 
d5-square.} 12. g5 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ge7d5][%csl Rf6] Moving the Knight away from 
controlling d5.} b4 $5 {[%csl Rc3] This seems like the only move, because if the 
f6-Knight moves away then Nd5 will be very dangerous!} 13. Ncd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 
{[%cal Gd5c7][%csl Rc7] Played in order to save the Knight, and this also 
attacks the Queen as well.} Bxd5 {You always need to get rid of the d5-Knight in 
the Sicilian if you can!} 15. Qxd5 {[%csl Ra8] Attacking the Rook on a8.} O-O 
{White is a pawn up, and attempts to exchange Queens.} 16. Qc4 Qa5 $13 {[%cal 
Bb4b3,Bd7e5,Ba8c8,Gc8c2,Gg7b2,Ge5f3,Ge5c4,Ga5e1][%csl Rc2,Rb2] Black has good 
compensation for many reasons: • 1) ...b3+ is going to be dangerous at any 
time for White. • 2) ...Ne5 is a decent idea in the position as well. • 3) 
... Bxb2 is coming. • 4) ...Rc8 is a neat idea as well, making use of the p-b4 
which is restricting the c2-pawn. The golden rule: ' Whenever you are material 
down, try to avoid any unnecessary exchanges '.} *

[Event "Short and Sweet: The Sicilian Dragon"]
[Site "S&S: The Sicilian Dragon"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Yugoslav: 8. Qd2, 9. g4"]
[Black "?"]
[Result "*"]
[SourceTitle "S&S: The Sicilian Dragon"]
[Source "Chessable.com"]
[Comment "short-and-sweet-the-sicilian-dragon/course/31190, variation/5714600"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and is also the 
most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for White's 
pieces faster.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 {And here we 
have our lovely system: The Dragon! It is one of the most played defences 
against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player began their Sicilian career playing 
the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's piece development and the clear plans 
available to him!} 6. Be3 Bg7 7. f3 a6 ({The main lines continue with} 7... O-O 
8. Qd2 Nc6) {or} (7... Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O {. Instead my suggestion is to play the 
sideline 7... a6, delaying castling and the development of our Knight to c6, 
instead starting immediate counterplay on the Queenside.}) {Why does 7 ... a6 
deserve an exclamation mark? • 1. It begins counterplay on the Queenside as 
quickly as possible. • 2. It delays castling Kingside, which means the attack 
on the Black King is going to be postponed, and then castling Queenside is an 
option for Black as well. • 3. It controls the square on b5, which is an 
important square that is attacked no less than three times by White. • 4. It 
depends on ideas rather than memorization. *Please note:* It is impossible to 
provide an answer to all the critical tries against the Sicilian Dragon, of 
which there are many, in a short and sweet course. Instead I have selected 20 
lines from my larger repertoire course that will give you a good sense of the 
typical ideas for Black in this dynamic opening!} 8. Qd2 Nbd7 9. g4 b5 10. h4 
{[%cal Bh4h5] The plan with h4 is one of the most dangerous lines that Black can 
face, and he really needs to know what to do here. The danger really comes from 
the early threat of h5, with an early opening of the h-file which follows the 
same attacking blueprint that White has followed before, except here he doesn't 
waste any time on early Queenside castling or developing his light-squared 
Bishop!} b4 {[%csl Rc3] Beginning counterplay on the other side of the board!} 
11. Na4 Ne5 {[%cal Gf6d7,Bh7h5,Ge5f3,Ge5c4][%csl Ge5] Improving the Knight and 
keeping an eye on both the c4-square and the f3-pawn. One more idea is: because 
the d7-Knight has now moved, ...h5 becomes possible because whenever White meets 
that by g5, then the f6-Knight can retreat to d7. Note: The e5-Knight cannot be 
easily kicked away by f4, because the g4-pawn will be captured by ... Nxg4.} 12. 
Qxb4 $6 {Strategically, this move gives a boost to the Black game because: It 
opens lines on a file where the White King will have to be placed (the b-file) 
because after the h4, g4 pushes, the Kingside is no longer an attractive place 
for the White King.} h5 {[%cal Gh5g4,Gf6g4,Ge5g4,Gc8g4][%csl Rg4] Attacking the 
g4-pawn four times, so White needs to move the pawn!} 13. g5 Nfd7 {[%csl 
Gd7,Rh7] And now there is a huge difference in the Knight's position. Much 
better on d7 rather than h7.} 14. O-O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gb8b2][%csl Rb4,Rb2] Black 
starts making use of the b-file.} 15. Qd2 Nb6 {[%cal Bb6a4,Bd8b6] In order to be 
able to bring the Queen in!} 16. Nxb6 Qxb6 {[%csl Rb2]} 17. Nb3 {Protecting the 
square on b2 while also creating a threat against the Queen on b6.} Qc7 $15 
{[%cal Be5c6,Ba6a5,Ba5a4,Gb8b2,Gg7b2][%csl Rb2,Rb3] Black has good compensation 
for the pawn: The Queenside is very open, so good attacking chances should be 
easy to find there. Our plan: ... Nc6 followed by ... a5-a4 in order to kick 
away the b3-Knight, and then make use of the b-file!} *

