1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and is also the 
most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for White's 
pieces faster.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 {And here we 
have our lovely system: The Dragon! It is one of the most played defences 
against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player began their Sicilian career playing 
the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's piece development and the clear plans 
available to him!} 6. Be2 Bg7 7. Be3 Nc6 8. Qd2 O-O 9. O-O-O Bd7 {Creating space 
for the Rook to come to c8.} 10. h4 h5 {Played to prevent any counterplay for 
White on the Kingside.} 11. f3 {This defends the e4-pawn while also supporting 
the g4 push.} Rc8 {We have reached a kind of Yugoslav attack, in which White 
developed the Bishop to e2 rather than to the very active diagonal on c4!} 12. 
g4 {Sacrificing pawns in order to open files on the Kingside.} hxg4 13. h5 {This 
is the point of the g4 sacrifice.} Nxh5 14. fxg4 Ng3 {[%cal Bg3e2,Gg3h1][%csl 
Rh1,Re2] Attacking both the Rook and the Bishop on e2.} 15. Rh3 Nxe2+ 16. Qxe2 
Nxd4 17. Bxd4 e5 {[%csl Gg7,Rd4] Played with the idea of keeping the g7-Bishop 
alive - it is a very important defensive piece which is needed to defend the h8 
square.} 18. Be3 Rxc3 $1 {With the idea of inflicting serious damage on the 
White Queenside.} 19. bxc3 Qc8 $17 {[%cal Gc8c3,Gc8g4][%csl Rg4,Rc3] Attacking 
both the pawn on g4 and the one on c3. *See the Jessel - Mestel Game.*} *

