1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and is also the 
most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for White's 
pieces faster.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 {And here we 
have our lovely system: The Dragon! It is one of the most played defences 
against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player began their Sicilian career playing 
the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's piece development and the clear plans 
available to him!} 6. Be2 {This is a quiet move, although not without bite. 
Black needs to know how to meet this system, because if he/she runs out of plans 
then they can easily find themselves outplayed in the early middlegame.} Bg7 7. 
O-O Nc6 8. Be3 O-O 9. Nb3 Be6 {[%cal Ba8c8,Ge6c4] Improving the Bishop and 
keeping an eye on the c4-square, while also creating space for the Rook to come 
to the c-file.} 10. f4 Rc8 $5 (10... Qc8 $5 {is a nice alternative, with the 
idea of playing ...Rd8 followed by ...d5.}) 11. f5 $5 {[%csl Re5] This is 
somewhat premature, and a possible drawback is that White now has a hole on e5. 
It's not difficult to imagine Black landing a powerful Knight on that square in 
the future.} Bd7 {[%cal Bc6e5][%csl Ge5]} 12. g4 {After committing to f5, White 
is obliged to go forward. It makes no sense to stop attacking now.} Ne5 {[%cal 
Bc8c3,Ge5c4][%csl Rc3,Gc4] Opening the file for the Rook for the later thematic 
sacrifice ...Rxc3! And keeping an eye on the c4-square.} 13. Bd4 {So as to avoid 
the ...Rxc3 threat, which would force bxc3, when Black will have caused huge 
damage to White's pawn structure.} Rxc3 $5 {[%cal Bf6e4][%csl Re4] Removing the 
protector of the e4-pawn.} 14. Bxc3 Nxe4 {[%csl Rc3] Attacking the c3-Bishop.} 
15. Bd4 Bc6 {[%cal Gc6h1] Putting the Bishop on the a8-h1 diagonal while also 
defending the e4-Knight.} 16. c3 b6 {[%cal Ba8h1,Bd8a8][%csl Ge4,Ge5] Creating 
more scope for the c6-Bishop while also defending the a7-pawn from attack. Black 
has very good compensation for the sacrificed exchange: • Two very powerful 
centralized Knights. • White's King is exposed. • Black has a superior pawn 
structure.} *

