1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 3. d4 {This move is considered the best move, and is also the 
most played one! The reason is that it opens lines and diagonals for White's 
pieces faster.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Attacking the e4-pawn.} 5. Nc3 g6 {And here we 
have our lovely system: The Dragon! It is one of the most played defences 
against 1. e4. Almost every Sicilian player began their Sicilian career playing 
the Dragon, because of the ease of Black's piece development and the clear plans 
available to him!} 6. Be2 {This is a quiet move, although not without bite. 
Black needs to know how to meet this system, because if he/she runs out of plans 
then they can easily find themselves outplayed in the early middlegame.} Bg7 7. 
O-O Nc6 8. Be3 O-O 9. Nb3 Be6 {Improving the Bishop and keeping an eye on the 
c4-square, while also creating space for the Rook to come to the c-file.} 10. f4 
Rc8 $5 11. g4 Na5 {Opening the c-file, eyeing the c4-square in order to meet f5 
by ...Bc4, and offering some exchanges which are going to be in Black's favour, 
because Black is the one who has less space.} 12. f5 {The idea behind an early 
f4.} Bc4 13. g5 {[%csl Rf6] White needs to keep attacking; this is the style 
that he has adopted after opting for the sharp f4 plan.} Nd7 {[%cal 
Bc4e2,Bg7c3][%csl Rc3] Saving the Knight and opening the diagonal for the Bishop 
on g7. Our threat is Bxe2 followed by Bxc3.} 14. Nxa5 Qxa5 15. Bxc4 Rxc4 {[%cal 
Gg7c3,Gc4e4][%csl Rc3,Re4] Once again exchanges work in Black's favour. Our 
threat is now taking on c3 followed by taking on e4.} 16. f6 {The only idea that 
keeps White in the game.} exf6 17. Qxd6 {[%csl Rd7]} Ne5 {[%cal Ga5e5][%csl Ge5] 
Played to save the Knight.} 18. gxf6 Rd8 {[%cal Ga5d8,Bg7f8][%csl Rd6] Attacking 
the Queen, while also creating space for the Bishop to come to f8.} 19. Qe7 Bf8 
$5 {Sacrificing the b7 pawn, in order to gain a tempo and bring the Bishop into 
the battle.} 20. Qxb7 Ng4 {[%csl Re3] Black starts the attack.} 21. Bf4 Qh5 
{[%cal Bd8d2,Gd2h2,Gh5h2,Gg4h2][%csl Rh2] Threatening Rd2.} 22. Qb5 {[%csl 
Rc4,Rh5] As White is now threatening the Rook on c4 and the Queen on h5, Black 
is now obliged to exchange Queens.} Qxb5 23. Nxb5 Rxc2 $17 {[%cal 
Gc2b2,Bf8c5,Gg4e3,Gg4f2][%csl Rb2,Rg1] Black is a pawn down, but as compensation 
has a much more active position. He is threatening Rxb2, and Bc5+ followed by 
Nf2.} *

